TypeScript is a typed superset of JavaScript. Explicitly typed languages force you to declare the types of your variables. Duck typing is a feature of many dynamic languages. It allows you to check the type of an object only by inspecting its behavior.
In TypeScript you can't use the Duck Typing feature, because it uses strict type checking. 
To use Duck Typing in TypeScript you need to use Reflection. 

```ts
var dog = new Dog();
var cat = new Cat();
if (dog instanceof Animal) {
	// dog is an Animal object
} else if (cat instanceof Animal) {
	// cat is an Animal object
} else {
	// They're both not Animals! 🐶🐱😱
}
```

```tsx
var dog = new Dog();
var cat = new Cat();
if (dog instanceof Animal) {
	// dog is an Animal object (since Dog is a subtype of Animal)
} else if (cat instanceof Animal) {
	// cat is an Animal object (since Cat is a subtype of Animal)
} else if (dog instanceof Dog && cat instanceof Cat) {
	// They're both Animals (since Dog and Cat are both subtypes of Animal) 🐶🐱😎
} else {
	// They're both not Animals! 🐶🐱😱
} 
```

